Your are training on images in Pascal VOC annotation format. From my point of view a negative example would be an image without bounding box annotation:
```
<annotation type="list"><annotation>
	<folder>JPEGImages</folder>
	<filename>jpeg-file.jpg</filename>
	<path>/path/to/your/jpeg-file.jpg</path>
	<source>
		<database>Unknown</database>
	</source>
	<size>
		<width>640</width>
		<height>480</height>
		<depth>3</depth>
	</size>
	<segmented>0</segmented>
</annotation>
```

Also every YOLO tile that doesn't have a used anchor box is a kind of negative example, which is the vast majority of tiles. In fact there is a paper out there on "focal loss" that makes positive hit anchor boxes higher in loss to balance the hit/no-hit imbalance ( https://arxiv.org/abs/1708.02002 ).
@david-hagar What you are saying is correct, but I think the "negative" images make sense if your model is predicting a set of classes in every image. This can happen if you train from scratch.

Yes trained some examples with only one class. Some of these images had no annotation. So these images are like negative examples. I haven't actively trained the network to not detect something, because YOLO is not designed for image classification. A wrong bounding box, however, should be punished by the mAP metric.

I'm also interested in training with negative samples. I'm working on a 1 class bounding box detection and wanted to improve training performance with negative, but kind of similar examples.

Therefore I did change the voc.py script around line 60 and add a train_mode boolean to the function parse_voc_annotation() which is per default False.

```
# train also on negative samples (w.o. labels)      added Andreas
          if train_mode is True:
                all_insts += [img]
            else:
                if len(img['object']) > 0:
                    all_insts += [img]
```

This should result to take all images for training but not for validation, when setting the boolean true only for getting train_ints, train_labels and NOT for valid_ints, valid_labels.

Of course this only works for manually splitted data, otherwise we have annotations without bounding boxes also in the validation set and this leads to an error for sure, due to the fact that the evaluation isn't made for annotations without any boxes.
